[1] USA (New York, Rockland county): new exposure sites in Nanuet and Monsey
Date: Fri 10 May 2019 11:17 AM EDT
Source: The Journal News, lohud [abridged, edited]
https://eu.lohud.com/story/news/local/rockland/2019/05/09/rockland-measles-new-exposure-sites-nanuet-and-monsey/1153270001/


Rockland county health officials on [Thu 9 May 2019] announced new measles exposure sites in Nanuet and Monsey. Anyone who visited the locations [see list at the source URL above] or used taxis at the times listed last week [week of 28 Apr 2019] may have been exposed to measles.

Jewish religious and political leaders, including the mayor of New Square, have supported vaccinations. The outbreak began in New Square and has primarily affected the Orthodox Jewish community in Spring Valley and Monsey.

The county, private physicians and health centers have administered more than 20 000 vaccinations since the outbreak began.

Local hospitals have taken measures to protect patients, including having 1st responders communicate to the hospital via an app that there is a potential measles case and screening or restricting visitors.

Rockland County Executive Ed Day has declared a state of emergency due to the outbreak. It is the 2nd declaration after the 1st, banning unvaccinated minors countywide from indoor public spaces, was struck down by the courts.

The current declaration targets those with measles or exposed to the virus in the affected areas and does not affect those with religious or medical exemptions.

State lawmakers are looking to end religious exemptions to vaccinations for school-aged children.

There are an additional 466 reported measles cases in Brooklyn as o[Mon 6 May 2019], and more than 22 000 vaccinations were administered there. These outbreaks were traced to Israel, where an outbreak has made more than 3900 people sick and resulted in at least 2 deaths.

As of 3 May 2019, there were 764 cases in 23 states in the US in the largest outbreak since 1994, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Measles was eliminated in the US in 2000, but outbreaks can occur when travelers bring measles from other countries.

[Byline: Rochel Leah Goldblatt]

